{
  "doc_id": "29436",
  "text": "Osteosarcoma is a life-threatening malignancy that most often occurs in teenagers [CITATION_1] . The prognosis of patients with osteosarcoma remains poor, in spite of advances in surgical treatment and the availability of new chemotherapeutic agents in recent decades. The overall relapse-free survival rate over 5 years is approximately 65% [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Ezrin also known as Villin2 (Vii2), located in the 6q25-6q26 of human chromosome, about 24kb and contains 13 exons. Its mRNA full length is 3166 bp. Located in between D6S442 and D6S281 [CITATION_4] ). Ezrin's relative molecular weight is about 81KD and composed of 585 amino acids, so it's the members of the ERM (Ezrin -Radixin -Moesin) family [CITATION_5] . ERM family is the member of band4.1 family, so its homology up to 75 ~ 80% with other members, with similar structure, as the connection of cytomembrane and actin cytoskeleton [CITATION_6] . Several studies have tried to investigate the clinical significance of Ezrin overexpression in osteosarcoma. Recent studies have come to inconsistent conclusions. In some studies, the increased levels of Ezrin , Yang Wu 1,2 protein at diagnosis resulted in an association with a worse clinical outcome [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] , whereas other reports either did not show any correlation between Ezrin and prognosis [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] or indicated a positive prognostic value for increased Ezrin expression at diagnosis [CITATION_13] . Most studies had a limited sample size, thus a quantitative synthesis using rigorous methods would be important to perform. We accordingly conducted a meta-analysis of all available studies relating Ezrin expression and Ezrin gene alterations with response to chemotherapy and/or clinical outcome, as defined by 2-year survival, because all studies were longitudinal over at least a 2-year period.",
